04593nam a22007455i 9780813554143DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20132013nju    fo  d z      eng d  a2012005100  a97808135541437 a10.36019/97808135541432doi  a(DE-B1597)530175  a(OCoLC)823725797  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ00aHV9104b.A27 2012 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a365.4209731 aAbrams, Laura S., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCompassionate Confinement :bA Year in the Life of Unit C /cBen Anderson-Nathe, Laura S. Abrams. 1aNew Brunswick, NJ : bRutgers University Press, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (188 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCritical Issues in Crime and Society00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1. History and Current Tensions in Juvenile Corrections -- tChapter 2. The Setting -- tChapter 3. Mixed Messages: “Therapy Speak” in a Correctional Milieu -- tChapter 4. “Take It Like a Man”: Masculinities, Treatment, and Crime -- tChapter 5. “Jumping through Hoops”: Identity, Self-Preservation, and Change -- tChapter 6. On the Outs -- tChapter 7. Rehabilitating Rehabilitation: What We Learned from Unit C -- tAppendix: Behind the Scenes: Reflections on Field Research in Action -- tReferences -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aTo date, knowledge of the everyday world of the juvenile correction institution has been extremely sparse. Compassionate Confinement brings to light the challenges and complexities inherent in the U.S. system of juvenile corrections. Building on over a year of field work at a boys’ residential facility, Laura S. Abrams and Ben Anderson-Nathe provide a context for contemporary institutions and highlight some of the system’s most troubling tensions. This ethnographic text utilizes narratives, observations, and case examples to illustrate the strain between treatment and correctional paradigms and the mixed messages regarding gender identity and masculinity that the youths are expected to navigate. Within this context, the authors use the boys’ stories to show various and unexpected pathways toward behavior change. While some residents clearly seized opportunities for self-transformation, others manipulated their way toward release, and faced substantial challenges when they returned home. Compassionate Confinement concludes with recommendations for rehabilitating this notoriously troubled system in light of the experiences of its most vulnerable stakeholders.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aJuvenile correctionszUnited States. 0aJuvenile delinquentsxRehabilitationzUnited States. 0aJuvenile delinquentsxRehabilitiationzUnited States. 0aJuvenile detention homeszUnited StatesvCase studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aAnderson-Nathe, Ben, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311068861040uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978081355414340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813554143423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780813554143.jpg  a978-3-11-068861-0  Rutgers University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK